{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"121ce500-44e0-11ed-85d1-9beb718d12e7","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"fbebbff4-2f99-46f9-9238-939fed9f36bf","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Hedging Exchange Rate Risk with Options","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"45feb21d-bc71-4063-8981-516ba7f9a81e"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"b3155eab-6d3e-48ad-8465-c97100a0396b","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Currency options","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" are another method that firms commonly use to manage exchange rate risk. Currency options, as with the stock options introduced in ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"aa4b644f-2423-4304-b9c1-9fabd31ec276","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Chapter 21","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"8c45fa00-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":", give the holder the right—but not the obligation—to exchange currency at a given exchange rate. Currency forward contracts allow firms to lock in a future exchange rate; currency options allow firms to insure themselves against the exchange rate moving beyond a certain level.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"6be73567-78d0-4953-8bb7-49468286cb1b"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-three","ref":"01a644bc-e0e0-4508-a35e-16bb849ee5d6","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Forward Contracts Versus Options","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"8dffdc5c-7eb1-4e93-860c-9c0d3ac32fc7"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"9c8b6ece-55cc-4cff-8389-ad63b664e47f","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"To demonstrate the difference between hedging with forward contracts and hedging with options, let’s examine a specific situation. In May 2008, the one-year forward exchange rate was $1.55 per euro. Instead of locking in this exchange rate using a forward contract, a firm that will need euros in one year can buy a call option on the euro, giving it the right to buy euros at a maximum price.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"2de3a406-85e0-47ce-a3d0-8592040e8d87","stage":{"ref":"60d9e1ab-7efc-46fe-b60b-3c65bac50cd6","sections":[{"ref":"cd5694d5-372a-4600-8099-30a55539d24a","rows":[{"ref":"414229b6-0ce1-4858-9e2c-c798456b002c","columns":[{"ref":"6a0e916c-64a7-459c-a5e2-65bada5993b9","stageElements":[{"ref":"17ca5036-9296-4c23-86f1-87235a67c5d5","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"122f600c-b7d0-456e-851e-5a05f8e5b542","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"9303c49d-f3cd-4b2e-935a-aacd6499ed59","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Currency options can be purchased over the counter from a bank or on an exchange. The Philadelphia Stock Exchange is one exchange offering currency options.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"1","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"e9ff8405-e3de-4233-86bf-2ca6aea0084d"},{"object":"text","text":" Suppose a one-year European call option on the euro with a strike price of $1.55 per euro trades for $0.05 per euro. That is, for a cost of $0.05 per euro, the firm can buy the right—but not the obligation—to purchase euros for $1.55 per euro in one year’s time. By doing so, the firm protects itself against a large increase in the value of the euro but still benefits if the euro declines.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"c0100b28-349b-4515-8b2d-c548876accfa"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"f023e971-b4ae-41b4-8101-ca7ee0fa0286","nodes":[{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"aca0ff04-5b4f-401b-9013-c6a69c6eeba2","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Table 23.1","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"b159b4d0-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":" shows the outcome from hedging with a call option if the actual exchange rate in one year is one of the values listed in the first column. If the spot exchange rate is less than the $1.55 per euro strike price of the option, then the firm will not exercise the option and will convert dollars to euros at the spot exchange rate. If the spot exchange rate is more than $1.55 per euro, the firm will exercise the option and convert dollars to euros at the rate of $1.55 per euro (see the second and third columns). We then add the initial cost of the option (fourth column) to determine the total dollar cost per euro paid by the firm (fifth column).","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"cb8fef94-9b5e-4fc3-8493-089a6d10fbff","stage":{"ref":"95b96278-d79a-46a5-b351-52b4d4bb0d63","sections":[{"ref":"51aca09b-c765-4f02-8179-06460b7f6f1c","rows":[{"ref":"719b77ed-cc73-4a11-b199-72dd601eeb28","columns":[{"ref":"5f7255b2-7918-4a1a-8e01-a71a0a33da78","stageElements":[{"ref":"2c8e14d5-bf0c-44d1-9ddc-9d5aa50333b6","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"55a51614-0d10-415b-8c1f-b304c0cc48e9","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"7e521377-adab-4bb9-989e-5677b9363a79","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"In computing the total cost, we have ignored the small amount of interest that could have been earned on the option premium.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"2","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"d53add05-675b-4729-b772-e7d201b86e18"}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"638b6057-42b8-40b0-ac40-5d840152d018"},{"type":"stage-element-table","config":{"activityLabel":"Table 23.1","instructions":"","tableCaptionText":"","activityTitle":"Cost of Euros ($/&#x20AC;) When Hedging with a Currency Option with a Strike Price of $1.55/&#x20AC; and an Initial Premium of $0.05/&#x20AC;","tableTitle":"","captions":"","credit":""},"value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"id":"ch23table01"},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{},"nodes":[{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"May 2009 Spot Exchange Rate","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-header","ref":"cfa42214-e995-43bf-b9dc-9662fe35eeb0"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Exercise Option?","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-header","ref":"325aebb5-b3e5-4bf0-945d-6c85c28f48ad"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Exchange Rate Taken","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"object":"block","type":"table-header","ref":"63839ed8-db81-4c04-9053-30fe00610104"},{"data":{"colSpan":1,"rowSpan":1},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","nodes":[{"object":"inline","type":"mathml-expression","data":{"mathML":"<math alttext=\"\" class=\"inlineequation\" display=\"inline\" altimg=\"../images/mm_altmath_652.png\" altimg-height=\"12\" altimg-width=\"18\"><mo>+</mo></math>","display":"inline","alt":"plus","svg":"<svg style=\"vertical-align: -0.186ex\" 